FBIS3-14875 "drsov040_a_94028" FBIS-SOV-94-040 Document Type:Daily Report 1 Mar 1994 RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS Russia Supports UN Observers in Middle East LD2802185894 Moscow Radio Moscow in Arabic 1400 GMT 28 Feb 94 LD2802185894 Moscow Radio Moscow Language: Arabic Article Type:BFN [Excerpts] Dear listeners, the Hebron massacre that cost the lives of dozens of Palestinians and wounded hundreds of others in the al-Ibrahimi Mosque on 25 February dealt a severe blow to the peace process in the Middle East. It is still not clear who committed this crime. The Israeli Government has set up a committee to look into the incident. However, it is totally clear that the Gaza-Jericho self-rule agreements are in danger after a lot of effort had been put into drawing them up. The PLO-Israeli talks were cut on all levels. The new round of Arab-Israeli talks in Washington that were due to take place today did not start. The delegations from Syria, Lebanon, and Jordan decided to discuss the implications of the current situation first; radical Arabs are demanding revenge. Tension in the occupied territories has increased, but it seems doubtful that terrorists will succeed in torpedoing the peace proces because this process is extremely important. [passage omitted] In 'Arafat's opinion, international forces have to be called in to the protect the Palestinians. Moscow believes this to be a good idea. Russian Foreign Minister Kozyrev stated that it was possible to send international observers to the area under UN supervision or the joint supervision of the United States and Russia. [passage omitted]
